ListIterator in Java

ListIterator is an interface in Java used to iterate over a List in both directions.

It is more powerful than Iterator and works only with List implementations like:

ArrayList
LinkedList
Why use ListIterator?

Use ListIterator when you need:

to move forward and backward
to modify elements during iteration
more control compared to Iterator
Creating ListIterator
import java.util.List;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.ListIterator;

List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");
list.add("Orange");

ListIterator<String> it = list.listIterator();
Main Methods
Forward traversal
it.hasNext(); // true if next exists
it.next();    // move forward
Backward traversal
it.hasPrevious(); // true if previous exists
it.previous();    // move backward
Get indexes
it.nextIndex();
it.previousIndex();
Modifying elements
it.set("Mango"); // replace current element
it.add("Kiwi");  // add element during iteration
Removing element
it.remove();

👉 works like in Iterator, removes last returned element

Example: Forward + Backward
ListIterator<String> it = list.listIterator();

// forward
while (it.hasNext()) {
    System.out.println(it.next());
}

// backward
while (it.hasPrevious()) {
    System.out.println(it.previous());
}
Iterator vs ListIterator
Feature	Iterator	ListIterator
Move forward	✅	✅
Move backward	❌	✅
Add elements	❌	✅
Replace elements	❌	✅
Works with all collections	✅	❌ (only List)
Important Notes
works only with List
allows modifying list safely during iteration
more powerful but slightly more complex than Iterator
Summary
ListIterator = advanced version of Iterator
can go forward and backward
can add, remove, update elements
used when you need full control over iteration
